# COMMIT FORMAT (AI agent must follow exactly)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# <type>: <summary in 50 chars or less>
#
# [optional body — 72-char wrap, explain WHY not WHAT]
#
# Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

# TYPE SELECTION RULES (pick the FIRST that matches):
#
#  feat     → production code adds a user-visible capability
#  fix      → production code corrects a defect or unintended behavior
#  refactor → production code changed with no behavior difference
#  test     → test files added/modified (no production code change)
#  docs     → doc/comment files only (no code change)
#  chore    → build, config, harness, migration meta (no prod code change)
#
# When multiple types apply, use the highest-impact one.
# Mixed changes (prod code + tests): use feat/fix/refactor, not test.
# Mixed changes (code + docs only): use feat/fix/refactor, not docs.

# SUBJECT LINE RULES:
#  - Korean or English, imperative mood: "추가" not "추가했다", "add" not "added"
#  - No trailing period
#  - 50 chars max (count in characters, not bytes)

# BODY RULES (include when the WHY is non-obvious):
#  - Blank line between subject and body
#  - Explain context, motivation, trade-offs — not what the diff shows
#  - 72-char line wrap

# Co-Authored-By line: ALWAYS include when Claude writes the commit.
